At the start of Week 5, the Democracy Clock stood at 7:50 p.m. It closed the week at 7:51 p.m., a movement of 1.3 minutes. On its face, that is a small shift. In substance, it marked the consolidation of several trends that had been building since Inauguration Day: the politicization and privatization of the civil service, the use of law as a weapon rather than a restraint, and the first organized steps toward undoing presidential term limits. The clock moved because these changes were structural, not symbolic. They altered who could say no to the president, who could be fired at will, and how long one leader might remain in office. That is what time meant this week.\
