These cuts were not random. They fell heavily on the parts of government that manage risk for the public. At USDA, employees working on the H5N1 bird flu outbreak were mistakenly fired and then hurriedly rehired. At the FAA, hundreds of workers responsible for air traffic control systems were let go, raising questions about aviation safety. At NIH and CDC, funding was frozen, projects delayed, and thousands of staff\'97especially those tied to diversity or early\uc0\u8209 career programs\'97were pushed out. USAID was allowed to furlough more than 2,000 workers, weakening foreign aid at a moment of global instability. In each case, the administration cited efficiency or poor performance. In each case, the pattern pointed to something else: a deliberate thinning of expertise and a warning that loyalty mattered more than competence. Workers were left more exposed and alone.\
