If DOGE and the executive orders were building a parallel state, the justice system was being bent to protect it. The most visible example was the Eric Adams case. Federal prosecutors in the Southern District of New York had charged the New York City mayor with corruption. Then, under pressure from Washington, Justice Department leaders ordered the case dropped. Public Integrity Section lawyers were reportedly locked in a room and given an hour to decide who would sign the dismissal or face termination. At least five of them resigned rather than comply. The acting U.S. attorney, Danielle Sassoon, also stepped down. A federal judge in Manhattan questioned the rationale for the dismissal, noting that it rested on policy considerations rather than the merits of the case. But the motion went forward, and the message was clear. Prosecutions of powerful figures could be undone if those figures became useful allies.\
