While institutions were being reshaped, the administration also moved against the time limits that define the presidency itself. At a White House event, Trump asked the audience whether he should run for a third term and mused aloud about the constitutional limits on his tenure. The next day, at CPAC, Steve Bannon endorsed a constitutional change to allow Trump to seek another term, backed by a \'93Third Term Project\'94 think tank. These were not yet formal amendments. But they were more than jokes. They were the first organized steps to normalize the idea that the Twenty\uc0\u8209 Second Amendment might be revised or circumvented for one man. In the Democracy Clock\'92s terms, this did not end term limits. It made their erosion a live project, with elite sponsors and a public stage. The taboo was broken in plain sight.\
